        <h2>1.5 Importance of multidisciplinary rehabilitation</h2>
        <div>
            <p>
                The rehabilitation process considers dysfunctions, disabilities and functional limitations present in the individual PwMS, as derived from the ICF<sup>22</sup>.
                Helping a PwMS achieve their maximum level of functionality depends upon a full assessment of medical, psychological and social issues; these diverse needs 
                are difficult for a single therapist to assess<sup>1</sup>. Multidisciplinary rehabilitation has been shown to have a positive effect on measures of 
                functional independence including sphincter control and self-care<sup>26</sup>. By adopting a multidisciplinary approach to MS rehabilitation, a PwMS will have 
                the opportunity to be assessed by rehabilitation professionals from a range of disciplines (e.g. vocational therapist, physiotherapist, social worker) 
                increasing the efficacy of rehabilitative interventions (figure 2)<sup>1</sup>. The most important point to remember is that the PwMS is at the heart 
                of the team and improving their QoL should be the focus of all team members.

            </p>
        </div>
        <br />
        <div class="nursetip">
            <a href="#" class="nursetipicon">click here</a>
            <p>
                Communicate effectively with all the rehabilitation team, and place the PwMS at the centre of that team. A weekly meeting, or circulated progress 
                report will keep all team members informed. Think about who the wider “team members” might include; such as family/friends, employers, tutors, 
                line managers or maybe local gym staff if community resources are being used. People do not exist in a rehabilitation “bubble”; they live in the world, 
                so be mindful of who has a role to play.
            </p>
        </div>

