        <p>
            Because of the multidisciplinary approach to rehabilitation, this module has been developed with the whole team in mind and is therefore intended as a foundation resource for all rehabilitation professionals such as physiatrists, occupational therapists, physical therapists, speech therapists, neurologists, nurses, and others involved in the management and rehabilitation of PwMS.
        </p>
        <div>
            <h3>1.5.1	The role of the nurse</h3>
            <p>
                The MS Nurse, along with the other healthcare professionals within the team, has a central role throughout a PwMS’s rehabilitation (Figure 3)<sup>27</sup>. The nurse can be involved in 
                many aspects of care from helping the PwMS think about their therapeutic goals to helping to implement short- and/or long-term rehabilitation programmes. 
            The MS Nurse will often be the ‘glue’ of the multidisciplinary rehabilitation team; acting to combine the recommendations and instructions from the 
            various professionals in the team into realistic and cohesive strategies. The MS Nurse also has an important role in educating the PwMS. From the time 
            of diagnosis (and throughout the trajectory of the disease) the MS Nurse helps to keep the PwMS informed regarding the substantial roles physical, 
            cognitive and emotional rehabilitation have on MS management.
            </p>

        </div>
