        <h2>Relationship with the PwMS</h2>
        <p>The nurse involved in the rehabilitation of the PwMS is a ‘change agent’ and patient advocate and champion, who enables the PwMS and important others to 
            interpret, evaluate, determine and agree problems, and identify the strategies and behaviours that will achieve good outcomes. </p>
        <p>The nurse remains a consistent, supportive presence throughout the journey of the PwMS. The nurse acts as navigator and broker to ensure the PwMS is able 
            to access the right rehabilitation resource at the right time and in the right way. The information and ongoing support provided by the nurse is often a 
            determining factor in the ability of the PwMS to understand and follow through with the treatment recommendations of the members of the rehabilitation team.</p>
        <p>An important role of the nurse is to promote self-care and achievable independence among PwMS. The nurse uses a collaborative approach that incorporates 
            abilities of the PwMS to make decisions about his or her healthcare to foster achievement of a high QoL.</p>
        <h2>
            Coordinator of care
        </h2>
       <%-- <p>From initial contact and across the MS trajectory, the nurse will assess, evaluate and convey the status, needs and interventions of the PwMS to members of 
            the rehabilitation team. </p>--%>
        <p>The nurse acts as a feedback loop for the team with a unique 360-degree view of the PwMS; their global health status, personal characteristics and assets, 
            societal and economical needs and support infrastructures. For example, the nurse should alert other team members to early signs of 
            cognitive changes that might interfere with the treatment plan and rehabilitation. The nurse can also help in detecting problems and barriers around the psychosocial needs of the PwMS’s support 
            system, family relationships and communication, and employment situation. The nurse also determines the PwMS’s need for personal assistance in terms of help 
            with personal care and/or household management. </p>
        <p>The nurse is most likely (BUT not always) to have the most intimate professional relationship with the PwMS. This enables them to advocate for timely, relevant 
            and cost-effective co-ordination of rehabilitation interventions that meet identified needs and place the PwMS at the heart of the team.</p>

         <br />
         <div class="nursetip">
            <a href="#" class="nursetipicon">click here</a>
            <p>
                Motivational interviewing, life coaching and regular validation are part of the nurse’s role in rehabilitation. It is also useful to “step outside” the medical model and consider non-medical activities alongside prescribed rehabilitation; such as art, singing or creative writing. It is important to encourage a balance of rest and relaxation alongside effort and to ensure things like sleep hygiene and nutrition are assessed as part of the rehabilitation process.
            </p>
        </div>

     

